data.title: Food was good, service could be a bit more friendly...
data.text:
This was my first time trying dim sum served in the traditional fashion (in metal carts). I've had dim sum with the paper method and to be honest, for first timers, the paper method is wayyyyy more efficient. What made it hard was how fast the servers were speaking and they have zero tolerance or time to explain to you slowly what any of the dishes really are. I mean, yes the eyes could see what it is, but there were a few things that looked so similar.

I will say everything I did try was good and hallajauh, not overly salty.
-Shrimp Dumplings
- Shrimp and scallop dumplings
- Shrimp rolls 
-Pork ribs
-steamed buns 
-egg rolls (I know, why waste the time right, but I had kids with me)
-Some kind of beef meatball (like I said, server went so fast, I just went with it)

I will have to give this place another try without my kids. I'll also read up more about what others order here and give the dim sum experience and this place another try.

data.title: Such a Wonderful Place for Dim Sum
data.text: I've eaten dim sum at numerous places in Chinatown in NYC, and find that the Mandarin Kitchen offers better food, and wonderful experience.  We tend to avoid the fried foods, and stick with things like steamed dumplings, shrimp, ribs, and veggies.  All of that is really quite good at that place.  Do be warned that the dishes and price can add up fast, and if you don't get to the Mandarin Kitchen early, be prepared to wait a while.  The time listed for Sunday brunch on TripAdvisor is incorrect, and caused us to wait about half an hour to be seated.  Every other time I've been here, I arrive about 15 minutes before they open, and are seated immediately.  So don't trust the times listed here, but go to the restaurant's website.

data.title: Not Comparable To East or West Coast
data.text: Minneapolis St Paul doesn't have good Chinese cuisine. Man. Kitchen is the best of a weak lot. The food is decent for a Midwest area. But can't compare to New York or Toronto or West Coast (not sure about Chicago). The dim sum is very ordinary. MSP does have quality Vietnamese and Korean food.The Chinese scene is run of the mill.

data.title: Authentic Mandarin Cuisine
data.text: Food was hot and very tasty. Rice was perfect. Gen Tso chicken very nicely done. I will be back and you should come here too.

data.title: Good place for family event on a weekday
data.text: We were glad that we had our family dinner at this place on a weekday. It's slow, so we didn't have to wait for a table or food. We had the Family Dinner for 6 and that was plenty for 7 people. The dinner came with a whole fish, lobster, beef chow fun, squid stir fried with preserved veggies... And they even served sweet soup for dessert. What a deal!

data.title: Great Cantonese Food
data.text: First time here, so two of us ordered 4 dishes to share and test. Best duck we have had in MN! Dumplings are an appetizer but very filling! Beef hotpot with Daikon would be a great Fall dish - hearty and fall off the bone. Buddhas Delight veggies were cooked perfect, the sauce was not as interesting as we would have expected. There were not  additional seasoning options on the table, like chili's just some soy sauce. Service was Ok and somewhat laconic, had to pry information about dishes out of the waiter.

data.title: Love coming here!
data.text: Always great fresh variety,  even the lunch combos are great! The menu is one of the most extensive in the twin cities.

data.title: The Best!
data.text:
The flavors are fantastic and the service excellent. (Ken is a great waiter)
The steamed black bean ribs, salt and pepper squid, pepper steak, pea tips and bitter melon soup were world class. 
I can't wait to return. 
Thank you Debby!

data.title: Among the Best Dim Sum I've Had
data.text: I have to say I'm surprised.  This place IS better than some of the dim sum I've eaten in SF and NYC.  They have excellent dumplings and you can't go wrong with the har gow or the siu mai.  I don't think I've had anything bad here.  Definitely GO if you're in the area.

data.title: Best Dim Sum in MN
data.text:
While not at the level of Dim Sum in Hong Kong, SF, NYC or Toronto, it is very good and truly the best we have found of all the Dim Sum places in Minnesota.  

The quality, selection and freshness is very good.  However, it seems many know this by the crowds and unless you arrive on weekend when they open, near 9:30am, there is nearly sure to be a wait.  Also, they are significantly more expensive than other Dim Sum places in the Twin Cities.

data.title: Large group
data.text: This place is great for a large group. We had 16 people and all shared food and paid $22 per person. We had a total of 23 dishes. The food was great! It's well seasoned. I'm giving 4 out of 5 because their service could have been better. We constantly had to ask for refills, napkins, etc.

data.title: Ok but expensevie
data.text:
A party of 4 and we ended up spending $250.00.... you not told the prices of stuff so of course your trying stuff and then the nest thing you know you stuck with a very large bill.... service was ok .... the food was no better or worse than going to a buffet....   I rather see a menu and pick what I want and know what I'm paying.... I can say I won't be back....

Also be aware you may stand an hour before you ever get a table

data.title: Good and pretty close to authentic Chinese
data.text: Their dim-sum is good and not too many places in the city to get it. I world not say amazing Chinese like in LA but for Minnesota it's tolerable and decent. I had a good experience here.

data.title: Authentic Cantonese food - delicious
data.text: The atmosphere is great, friendly staff, Dim Sum on Saturday and Sunday morning are the best I have been eating outside of Asia. The food is great, especially their preparation of some of the seafood dishes are out of this world. I loved their fried rice, but also their Sole preparation and size is great. Definitely a place to eat if you like the authentic Chinese cuisine.

data.title: Dim Sum Win Some
data.text: We LOVE this place... It reminds us of when we lived in Hong Kong with the noises, smells, business, and tasty dim sum. We usually head here once a month on Sunday's around 9-10am. The price includes tip and comes to roughly 10-15usd a person. I highly recommend this place.

data.title: Outstanding dim sum in MSP
data.text: Mandarin is an amazing restaurant - authentic Chinese, service is prompt.  It's known for dim sum and other dishes  - very popular with the locals in this area.  A wide variety of dishes that you have to try.   When you walk in, you get to see several aquariums with lobster, crab, eel, etc.  Loved the char sieu (bbq pork), steamed dumpling with chicken and veg.  Several seafood options too.  Highly recommended having dim sum here .  Make sure you end with the fruit tart which is incredible.

data.title: Has Been Better
data.text: I have been thinking about how to write this review. We have been fans of dim sum for many years and have been to restaurants in other cities for this special treat -- Washington, DC; San Francisco; Chicago. We have been to this restaurant several times for dim sum and enjoyed our meals. We had dim sum here recently and had a meal that was so less than good, we offered to pay for the entire table so that our friends were not obligated. Standards were okay -- pork and shrimp shu mei and sticky rice, for example. But the duck was very tough and had little meat on the bones and other dumpling dishes were bland. The dish we most enjoyed was a sesame seaweed salad. Having had only one of several dishes sampled to call out as enjoyable means we won't be returning. And we're sorry to have to say it.

data.title: Consistent dim sum
data.text: I have been to this restaurant many times, mostly for dim sum, once in a while for dinner.  Their dim sum is served on Sat and Sun only and is very consistent. The skin on the har gow should be much thinner and their egg tarts should be more browned but given that most everything else is pretty good, I don't mind it so much.  This place is not on the same level as New York or San Francisco but it's one of the best in MN.  The carts come around frequently so you could start eating almost from the second you are seated.  I prefer tables in the main dining room vs the 2 private rooms.  Service is not very friendly but they are efficient.  Tea is included.  Tax and tip is also included no matter the size of your party.  Unless you ask, you are not given regular menus if you are there during dim sum time.  I just found out that they recently started opening at 9:30am.  If you don't want to wait, you need to get there by that time.  Even 15 minutes later and you may have to wait.  They fill up in a heartbeat.  Not sure if they take reservations.  Go there for dinners too.  Have had many good meals there.  Plus you are given complimentary soup and Chinese desserts (only with dinner entrees, I think).

data.title: Mediocre food and too much food
data.text: This place has been around for years and am not sure why.  I guess because lots of people go for the Dim Sum.  The food is mediocre at best and the portions are way too large.  A person can't seem to get a smaller portion of something but I guess one can always get a to go box.  It's never the same though, just wish one could finish in the place.

data.title: DimSum
data.text: Food was okay.  The dim sum doesn't compare to Chicago, San Francisco or Windsor but not bad for Minnesota.  It was greasy and not cheap.  Place was very crowded.
